{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3840277-0714-44d4-945e-4549b8a65838","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis gives live CPU/GC/threadpool metrics without a full trace.\n\n### Tips\n- If the container lacks the .NET SDK, copy `dotnet-trace` in via `kubectl cp` or use a [sidecar/ephemeral debug container](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-application/debug-running-pod/#ephemeral-container).\n- To get the file out: `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- For Windows containers specifically, ensure the `dotnet` CLI is on `PATH` inside the container image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"238012c5-20c0-4d59-ab93-51ea87d50b97","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code task. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"ABC7:12E269:1397817:15FFCB4:6A067026"},"id":"d88532a8-2fb6-4172-bf02-d60cc391ff49","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:00:34.303Z","parentId":"7c9cbbc4-3929-4903-821c-8f33d9d62524"}
